                        <interp inst="t18800301-name-458" type="given" value="IDEN"></interp>IDEN PAYNE</persName>
                  </hi>. In October last I was assistant to Mr. Clark, shoe manufacturer, of Northampton—about July last year Wymark came there and wished to see samples of goods suitable for the Cape trade—I showed him some, and told him the prices—we afterwards received this letter (<hi rend="italic">This was dated 30th August</hi>, 1879, <hi rend="italic">from</hi> 30, <hi rend="italic">New Bridge Street, ordering samples to be sent to J. O. Hodges at the above address and signed William Wymark</hi>)—the samples were sent, about 13 pairs, amounting to about 9<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—we then received this letter of 11th September (<hi rend="italic">This was also from Wymark, and stated that Mr. Hodges was away, but would see him to-morrow and write fully</hi>)—we. then received these letters of September 13th and 17th, October 2nd and 9th, the latter signed J. E. Hodges) ordering goods to the amount of 34<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 17<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—we did not supply them—we determined to have the money first—we never got the money for the samples—I have seen part of them since at Russell's, the pawnbroker's, in Fore Street—theee (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) are the letters we sent in the course of the transaction: some addressed to Wymark and the others to Hodges:</p>
